  "footnotes": [
    "Northern Crusade (1198–1290): a series of campaigns by the Teutonic Order, Livonian Brothers of the Sword, and Danish crown to Christianize the Baltic peoples; the conquest of Estonia and Latvia was brutal and systematic; the Lithuanians resisted successfully until voluntary conversion in 1386–1387 as part of the Polish union",
    "Battle of Grunwald (1410): the Grand Duchy of Lithuania and the Kingdom of Poland decisively defeated the Teutonic Knights, ending the Order's expansion eastward; one of the largest battles of medieval Europe; deeply embedded in Polish, Lithuanian, and Belarusian national memory",
    "Duchy of Courland-Semigallia (1562–1795): a Polish vassal duchy in western Latvia notable for its overseas colonial ambitions — it established colonies in Gambia (Fort Jacob) and Tobago in the 17th century, remarkable achievements for a small landlocked duchy",
    "Soviet deportations (June 1941 & March 1949): the NKVD deported tens of thousands of Baltic civilians to Siberia and Kazakhstan in two major operations; the 1949 'Operation Priboi' targeted farming families as part of forced collectivisation, deporting roughly 90,000 people from all three republics in a single week",
    "Singing Revolution (1987–1991): the Baltic independence movements were characterized by mass nonviolent demonstrations, most famously the Baltic Way (23 August 1989) in which approximately two million people formed a 675-km human chain across all three republics on the 50th anniversary of the Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact",
    "Lithuanian Provisional Government (June 1941): when German forces arrived, Lithuanian nationalists declared a government and broadcast independence on radio; it lasted six weeks before the Nazis dissolved it and installed direct occupation — Germany was unwilling to allow even puppet Baltic states"
  ]
